          "body": "Having established the principle of individual accountability through the static case study, Ezekiel now introduces the dynamic dimension: moral trajectories can reverse. Verses 21-23 describe the wicked man who turns (*shuv*) from all his sins, keeps God's statutes, and practices justice. The verdict is unambiguous: 'He shall surely live; he shall not die' (v. 21). More remarkably, 'all his transgressions which he has committed will not be remembered against him' (v. 22). This is not merely judicial tolerance; it is divine forgetting of the record. Verse 23 then provides the theological ground for the entire offer: 'Do I have any pleasure in the death of the wicked... rather than that he should turn from his ways and live?' The answer is implicit and irresistible: God's desire for repentance and life dwarfs any punitive appetite. Verses 24-26 then apply the same dynamic in reverse: the righteous man who turns away from his righteousness and commits abominations dies, and his prior righteous deeds are not remembered. This is the chapter's most uncomfortable teaching. It does not teach that a truly regenerate believer loses his salvation — the theological debate about the referent of 'righteous man' is real and significant (see Interpretation). What it does teach is that there is no moral capital from past righteousness that immunizes a person against the consequences of present apostasy. Verses 25-29 record the community's ongoing protest — 'the way of the Lord is not right' — and God's double counter-charge: it is Israel's ways that are not right. The repetition of the objection (vv. 25, 29) signals the depth of the community's resistance and sets up the direct appeal that follows."
